<section xml:id="section-solving-quadratic-equations-by-factoring">

    <title>Solving Quadratic Equations by Factoring</title>

    <objectives>
        <title>PCC Course Content and Outcome Guide</title>
        <ul>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equations-using-zero-product-principle" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-check-solutions-for-quadratic-equations" /></li>
            <li><xref ref="mth65-solve-quadratic-equation-applications" /></li>
            <!-- TODO: Remove trig functions from CCOG statements -->
        </ul>
    </objectives>

    <p>We have learned how to factor trinomials like <m>x^2+5x+6</m> into <m>(x+2)(x+3)</m>. This skill is needed to solve an equation like <m>x^2+5x+6=0</m>, which is a quadratic equation. A <term>quadratic equation</term> is is an equation that can be algebraically rearranged, as needed, to have the form <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m>, where <m>a</m>, <m>b</m>, and <m>c</m> are all real numbers and <m>a\neq0</m>. The form <m>ax^2+bx+c=0</m> is called the <term>standard form</term> of a quadratic equation.</p>

    <figure>
        <caption>Alternative Video Lesson</caption>
        <video youtube="2ZzuZvz33X0"/>
    </figure>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Identify which of the items are quadratic equations.</p>
            <ul>
                <li><p><m>2x^2+5x=7</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>5-2x=3</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>15-x^3=3x^2+9x</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>(x+3)(x-4)=0</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>x(x+1)(x-1)=0</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>x^2-5x+6</m></p></li>
                <li><p><m>(2x-3)(x+5)=12</m></p></li>
            </ul>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ul>
                <li><p><m>2x^2+5x=7</m> <em>is</em> a quadratic equation. To write it in standard form, simply subtract <m>7</m> from both sides.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>5-2x=3</m> <em>is not</em> quadratic. It is a linear equation and cannot be converted into a quadratic equation.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>15-x^3=3x^2+9x</m> <em>is not</em> a quadratic equation. The <m>x^3</m> makes it so that no algebraic manipulation can turn it into a quadratic equation.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>(x+3)(x-4)=0</m> <em>is</em> a quadratic equation. If you multiply the left-hand side of the equation, you would get something in standard form right away.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>x(x+1)(x-1)=0</m> <em>is not</em> a quadratic equation. If you multiply the left-hand side of the equation, you can see that you will have an expression with <m>x^3</m>, which automatically makes it not quadratic.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>x^2-5x+6</m> <em>is not</em> a quadratic <em>equation</em>, it's a quadratic <em>expression</em>.</p></li>
                <li><p><m>(2x-3)(x+5)=12</m> <em>is</em> a quadratic equation. Multiplying out the left-hand side, and moving over the <m>12</m>, you can imagine that there would be a <m>2x^2</m> in the left-hand side expression.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <p>A physics class launches a tennis ball from a rooftop that is <m>80</m> feet above the ground. They fire it directly upward at a speed of <m>64</m> feet per second and measure the time it takes for the ball to hit the ground below. We can model the height of the tennis ball, <m>h</m>, in feet, with the quadratic equation, <m>h=-16t^2+64t+80</m>, where <m>t</m> represents the time in seconds after the launch. Using the model we can predict when the ball will hit the ground.</p>

