    <p>The ground has a height of <m>0</m>, or <m>h=0</m>. We will substitute <m>0</m> for <m>h</m> in the equation and we have
        <me>-16t^2+64t+80=0</me>
    We need to solve this quadratic equation for <m>t</m> to find when the ball will hit the ground.</p>

    <p>The key strategy for solving a <em>linear</em> equation is to separate the variable terms from the constant terms on either side of the equal sign. It turns out that this same method <em>will not work</em> for quadratic equations. Fortunately, we already have spent a good amount of time discussing a method that <em>will</em> work: factoring. If we can factor the polynomial on the left-hand side, we will be on the home stretch to solving the whole equation.
    </p>

    <p>We will look for a common factor first, and see that we can factor out <m>-16</m>. Then we can finish factoring the trinomial:<md>
        <mrow>-16t^2+64t+80\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(t^2-4t-5)\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(t+1)(t-5)\amp=0</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>In order to solve the equation, we need to understand a property. This property explains why it was <em>incredibly important</em> to <m>not</m> move the <m>80</m> in our example over to the other side of the equation before trying to factor.</p>

    <theorem xml:id="theorem-zero-product-property">
        <title>The Zero Product Property</title>
        <idx><h>The Zero Product Property</h></idx>
        <statement>
            <p>If the product of two or more numbers is equal to zero, then at least one of the numbers must be zero.</p>
        </statement>
    </theorem>

    <p>To understand this property, let's look at a few products:
        <md>
            <mrow>4\cdot7\amp=28\amp\amp\amp4\cdot0\amp=0\amp\amp\amp4\cdot7\cdot3\amp=84</mrow>
            <mrow>0\cdot7\amp=0\amp\amp\amp-4\cdot0\amp=0\amp\amp\amp4\cdot0\cdot3\amp=0</mrow>
        </md>
    If none of the factors is zero, it is impossible to get a product of zero. The only way to get a product of zero is if one of the factors is zero. This property is unique to the number zero and can be used no matter how many numbers are multiplied together.</p>

    <p>Now we can see the value of factoring. We have three factors in our equation <m>-16(t+1)(t-5)=0</m>. The first factor is the number <m>-16</m>. The second and third factors, <m>t+1</m> and <m>t-5</m>, are expressions that represent numbers. Since the product of the three factors is equal to zero, one of the factors must be zero.</p>

    <p>Since <m>-16</m> cannot be <m>0</m>, either <m>t+1</m> or <m>t-5</m> must be <m>0</m>. This gives us two equations to solve: 
        <md>
            <mrow>t+1\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t-5\amp=0</mrow>
            <mrow>t+1\subtractright{1}\amp=0\subtractright{1}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t-5\addright{5}\amp=0\addright{5}</mrow>
            <mrow>t\amp=-1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp t\amp=5</mrow>
        </md>
    We have found two solutions, <m>-1</m> and <m>5</m>. A quadratic equation will have at most two linear factors, not including any constants, so it can have up to two solutions.</p>

    <p>Let's check each of our two solutions <m>-1</m> and <m>5</m>:<md>
        <mrow>-16t^2+64t+80\amp=0\amp\amp\amp-16t^2+64t+80\amp=0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(\substitute{-1})^2+64(\substitute{-1})+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-16(\substitute{5})^2+64(\substitute{5})+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16(1)-64+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-16(25)+320+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>-16-64+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0\amp\amp\amp-400+320+80\amp\stackrel{?}{=}0</mrow>
        <mrow>0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0\amp\amp\amp0\amp\stackrel{\checkmark}{=}0</mrow>
    </md></p>

    <p>We have verified our solutions. While there are two solutions to the equation, the solution <m>-1</m> is not relevant to this physics model because it is a negative time which would tell us something about the ball's height <em>before</em> it was launched. The solution <m>5</m> does make sense. According to the model, the tennis ball will hit the ground <m>5</m> seconds after it is launched.</p>
    <remark>
        <p>As a brief summary, to solve a quadratic equation using factoring, first simplify the equation and move all of the terms onto one side so that the other side is <m>0</m>. Then factor and use the zero product property to solve.</p>
    </remark>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-5x-14=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>x^2-5x-14\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-7)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-7\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x-7\addright{7}\amp=0\addright{7}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\subtractright{2}\amp=0\subtractright{2}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=7\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-2</mrow></md>
                The solutions are <m>-2</m> and <m>7</m>, so the solution set is written as <m>\{-2, 7\}.</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>If the two factors of a polynomial happen to be the same, the equation will only have one solution. Let's look at an example of that.</p>

    <example>
        <title>A Quadratic Equation with Only One Solution</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-10x+25=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>x^2-10x+25\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-5)(x-5)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-5)^2\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x-5\addright{5}\amp=0\addright{5}</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=5</mrow></md>
                The solution is <m>5</m>, so the solution set is written as <m>\{5\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factor Out a Common Factor</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>5x^2+55x+120=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p><md>
                <mrow>5x^2+55x+120\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>5(x^2+11x+24)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>5(x+8)(x+3)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+8\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+3\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=-3</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-8, -3\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring Using the AC Method</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>3x^2-7x+2=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
                <p>Recall that we multiply <m>3\cdot2=6</m> and find a factor pair that multiplies to <m>6</m> and adds to <m>-7</m>. The factors are <m>-6</m> and <m>-1</m>. We use the two factors to replace the middle term with <m>-6x</m> and <m>-x</m>.<md>
                <mrow>3x^2-7x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x^2-6x-x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(3x^2-6x)+(-x+2)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x(x-2)-1(x-2)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(3x-1)(x-2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>3x-1\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>3x\amp=1\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=\frac{1}{3}\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\left\{\frac{1}{3}, 2\right\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <p>So far the equations have been written in standard form, which is 
        <me>ax^2+bx+c=0</me>
    If an equation is not given in standard form then we must rearrange it in order to use the Zero Product Property.</p>

    <example>
        <title>Writing in Standard Form</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2-10x=24</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>To use the zero product property, we must have a zero on one side of the equation.<md>
                <mrow>x^2-10x\amp=24</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-10x\subtractright{24}\amp=24\subtractright{24}</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-10x-24\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x-12)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x-12\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=12\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x=\amp-2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-2, 12\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Writing in Standard Form Part II</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>(x+4)(x-3)=18</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>This time we must multiply the left side and subtract <m>18</m> from both sides.<md>
                <mrow>(x+4)(x-3)\amp=18</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-12\amp=18</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-12\subtractright{18}\amp=18\subtractright{18}</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2+x-30\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x+6)(x-5)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+6\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-6\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=5</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-6, 5\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring a Polynomial with Two Terms</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>2x^2=5x</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>It may be tempting to divide both sides of the equation by <m>x</m>. but if we did we would lose one of the solutions! As a general rule, never divide an equation by a variable in the solving process. Instead, we will put the equation in standard form.<md>
                <mrow>2x^2\amp=5x</mrow>
                <mrow>2x^2\subtractright{5x}\amp=5x\subtractright{5x}</mrow>
                <mrow>2x^2-5x\amp=0</mrow>
                <intertext>Since there are only two terms, we will look for a common factor.</intertext>
                <mrow>x(2x-5)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x-5\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp 2x\amp=5</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=\frac{5}{2}</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\left\{0, \frac{5}{2}\right\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Factoring a Special Polynomial</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>x^2=9</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>We will learn an easier method to solve this problem later. For now, we will put the equation in standard form and use factoring.<md>
                <mrow>x^2\amp=9</mrow>
                <mrow>x^2-9\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>(x+3)(x-3)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+3\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-3\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-3\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=3</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-3, 3\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Solving an Equation With a Higher Degree</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Solve <m>2x^3-10x^2-28x=0</m> by factoring.</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>Although this equation is not quadratic, it does factor so we can solve it by factoring.<md>
                <mrow>2x^3-10x^2-28x\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>2x(x^2-5x-14)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>2x(x-7)(x+2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>2x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-7\amp=0\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x+2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=7\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x\amp=-2</mrow></md>
                The solution set is <m>\{-2, 0, 7\}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>Kicking it on Mars</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Some time in the recent past, Forrest traveled to Mars for a vacation with his kids, Hunter and Kelly, who wanted to kick a soccer ball around in the comparatively reduced gravity.<!-- Mars was lush and green after the terraforming, and the kids went out into a grassy field with their dad. --> Kelly stood at point <m>K</m> and kicked the ball over her dad standing at point <m>F</m> to Hunter standing at point <m>H</m>. The height of the ball off the ground, <m>h</m> in feet, can be modeled by the equation <m>h=-0.01\left(x^2-70x-1800\right)</m>, where <m>x</m> is how far to the right the ball is from Forrest. Note that distances to the left of Forrest will be negative.</p>

            <ol>
                <li><p>Find out how high the ball was above the ground when it passed over Forrest's head.</p></li>
                <li><p>Find the distance from Kelly to Hunter.</p></li>
            </ol>
            <figure>
                <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars</caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
    
                            \begin{axis}[axis x line=none,axis y line=none,xmin=-30, xmax=100, ymin=-5, ymax=35, height=0.2*\textwidth]

                            \addplot[domain=-20:90, mark=*, samples=15, smooth, dashed, thin, color=red]  {-0.01*(x^2-70*x-1800};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(-20,0)} node[above left] {K};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(0,0)} node[above] {F};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(90,0)} node[above right] {H};
                            \addplot[color=green!80!black, thick] coordinates{(-30,0)(100,0)};
    
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </statement>
        <solution>
            <ol>
                <li><p>The ball was neither left nor right of Forrest when it went over him, so <m>x=0</m>. Plugging that value into our equation for <m>x</m>,
                <md>
                    <mrow>h\amp=-0.01\left(0^2-70(0)-1800\right)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=-0.01(-1800)</mrow>
                    <mrow>\amp=18</mrow>
                </md>
                It seems that the soccer ball was <m>18</m> feet above the ground when it flew over Forrest.</p></li>
                <li><p>The distance from Kelly to Hunter is the same as the distance from point <m>K</m> to point <m>H</m>. These are the horizontal intercepts of the graph of the given formula: <m>h=-0.01\left(x^2-70x-1800\right)</m>. To find the horizontal intercepts, set <m>h=0</m> and solve for <m>x</m>.
                <md>
                    <mrow>0=-0.01\left(x^2-70x-1800\right)</mrow>
                    <intertext><p>Note that we can divide by <m>-0.01</m> on both sides of the equation to simplify.</p></intertext>
                    <mrow>0\amp=x^2-70x-1800</mrow>
                    <mrow>0\amp=(x-90)(x+20)</mrow>
                    <intertext>So, either:</intertext>
                    <mrow>x-90\amp=0\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x+20\amp=0</mrow>
                    <mrow>x\amp=90\amp\text{or}\amp\amp x\amp=-20</mrow>
                </md>
                Since the <m>x</m>-values are how far right or left the points are from Forrest, Kelly is standing <m>20</m> feet left of Forrest and Hunter is standing <m>90</m> feet right of Forrest. Thus, the two kids are <m>110</m> feet apart.
                </p></li>
            </ol>
            <p>It is worth noting that if this same kick, with same initial force at the same angle, took place on Earth, the ball would have traveled less than <m>30</m> feet from Kelly before landing!</p>
            <figure>
                <caption>A Soccer Kick on Mars and the Same Kick on Earth</caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                            <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
    
                            \begin{axis}[axis x line=middle,axis y line=middle,xmin=-30, xmax=100, ymin=-10, ymax=40, grid=both, xtick={-20,0,...,80}, ytick={10,20,30}, minor xtick={-30,-20,...,100}, minor ytick={-10,0,...,40}, height=0.2*\textwidth]

                            \addplot[domain=-20:90, mark=*, samples=15, smooth, dashed, thin, color=red]  {-0.01*(x^2-70*x-1800} node[above left] {Mars};
                            \addplot[color=green!80!black, thick] coordinates{(-30,0)(100,0)};
                            \addplot[domain=-20:8.039, mark=*, samples=7, smooth, dashed, thin, color=blue] {-0.03857558*x^2-0.46141508*x+6.2019337} node[above right] {Earth};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(-20,0)};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(0,0)};
                            \addplot[mark=*, color=green!40!black] coordinates{(90,0)};
    
                            \end{axis}
                            \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <title>An Area Application</title>
        <statement>
            <p>Rajesh has a hot tub and he wants to build a deck around it. The hot tub is <quantity><mag>7</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> by <quantity><mag>5</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> and it is covered by a roof that is <quantity><mag>99</mag><unit base="foot" exp="2"/></quantity>. How wide can he make the deck so that it will be covered by the roof?</p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>We will define <m>x</m> to represent the width of the deck (in feet). Here is a diagram to help us understand the scenario.</p>
            <figure>
                <caption>Diagram for the Deck</caption>
                <image width="70%">
                    <latex-image-code>
                        <![CDATA[\begin{tikzpicture}
                            \draw [color=blue, very thick, fill=gray!30!white] (1,1) rectangle (12,10);
                            \draw [very thick, fill=white!80!blue] (3,3) rectangle (10,8);
                            \draw (6.5,3.5) node {$7$ ft};
                            \draw (9.5,5.5) node {$5$ ft};
                            \draw [color=blue] (6.5,2) node {$x$};
                            \draw [color=blue] (6.5,9) node {$x$};
                            \draw [color=blue] (2,5.5) node {$x$};
                            \draw [color=blue] (11,5.5) node {$x$};
                            \draw [dotted, <->, color=blue, thick] (1,5) to (3,5);
                            \draw [dotted, <->, color=blue, thick] (10,5) to (12,5);
                            \draw [dotted, <->, color=blue, thick] (7,1) to (7,3);
                            \draw [dotted, <->, color=blue, thick] (7,8) to (7,10);
                        \end{tikzpicture}]]>
                    </latex-image-code>
                </image>
            </figure>

            <p>The overall length is <m>7+2x</m> feet, because Rajesh is adding <m>x</m> feet on each side. Similarly, the overall width is <m>5+2x</m> feet.</p>

            <p>The formula for the area of a rectangle is <m>\text{area}=\text{length}\cdot\text{width}</m>. Since the total area of the roof is <quantity><mag>99</mag><unit base="foot" exp="2"/></quantity>, we can write and solve the equation:<md>
                <mrow>(7+2x)(5+2x)=99</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x+35=99</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x+35\subtractright{99}\amp=99\subtractright{99}</mrow>
                <mrow>4x^2+24x-64\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>4(x^2+6x-16)\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>4(x+8)(x-2)\amp=0</mrow></md><md>
                <mrow>x+8\amp=0\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x-2\amp=0</mrow>
                <mrow>x\amp=-8\amp\amp\text{or}\amp x\amp=2</mrow>
            </md></p>

            <p>Since a length cannot be negative, we take <m>x=2</m> as the only applicable solution. Rajesh should make the deck <quantity><mag>2</mag><unit base="foot"/></quantity> wide on each side to fit under the roof.</p>
        </solution>
    </example>

